I came up with a less-than-ideal but better-than-exporting workaround.

**jest.config.js**

```lang-js
module.exports = {
  // ...
  globals: {
    TEST: true,
    // ...
  }
};
```

**global.d.ts**
```lang-ts
export {};
declare global {
  const TEST: boolean;
  // ...
}
```

**webpack.config.js**

```lang-js
const { DefinePlugin } = require(&#39;webpack&#39;);
module.exports = {
  // ...
  plugins: [
    new DefinePlugin({ TEST: &#39;false&#39; })
  ]
};
```

**my-module.ts**

```lang-ts
function myNonExportedFunction() {
  // ...
}

if (TEST) {
  module.exports.myNonExportedFunction = myNonExportedFunction;
}
```

**__tests__/module.ts**

```lang-ts
const { myNonExportedFunction } = require(&#39;../my-module&#39;);

test(&#39;myNonExportedFunction&#39;, () =&gt; {
  // ...
});
```

The two drawbacks to this method are:

1. you&#39;re including minimal test code in your production code (though webpack can remove code based on constants)

2. you lose strong typing on your non-exported functions, though you lose that type-safety with rewire anyway

