I&#39;m not sure to fully understand what you are trying to achieve. What I understand is that the user can choose his menu and customize with some optional ingredients (like a Subway sandwich?).

What I would advise is to clearly split your data (i.e. the choices available) and what the user puts in its cart (i.e. input data).

Since you tagged your question with Angular/TypeScript, I would define TypeScript interfaces to help think about your data structure:

```ts
interface Ingredient {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  // In your code, you used strings for the following properties
  // but I think number would better fit (if you wish to sum, multiply, etc).
  price: number; 
  hour: number;
}

interface Menu {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  price: number; 
  hour: number;
  timCook: number;
  supp: Ingredient[]; // An array of ingredients
}
```

You can then declare your base data like this:

```ts
// An array of Menu
const products: Menu[] = [
  {
      id: 0, name: &#39;Salami&#39;, price: 8, hour: null, timCook: null,
      supp:[
        { id: 1123, name: &#39;fromage&#39;, price: 5, hour: null },
        { id: 11234, name: &#39;bbq&#39;, price: 10, hour: null },
      ],
  },
];
```

Fine. Now, how to store what the user selected? We don&#39;t need to store every properties again (single source of truth). We just keep a reference to it : luckily, we have `id` for that. Let&#39;s define some interfaces:

```ts
interface MenuSelection {
  id: number; // Id. of the Menu the user selected
  supp: number[]; // Array of Ingredients id. the user selected
}

type Cart = MenuSelection[]; // The shopping cart is an array of MenuSelection
```

And now the logic:

```ts
const cart: Cart = [] // Start with empty cart

// Let&#39;s say your user selected Menu 0 and Ingredient 1123
// You&#39;ll have to wire with your interface to build such object
const menuSelection: MenuSelection = {
  id: 0,
  supp: [1123],
};

// Add a selection to the Cart
cart.push(menuSelection);
```

You can quite easily then build methods to retrieve the full `Menu` and `Ingredient` from the selected ids. if you want to show what&#39;s inside the shopping cart.

